  "text": "Baker's method was originally designed to give PTASs for a host of NP-hard optimization problems on planar graphs like minimum vertex cover, minimum dominating set, maximum independent set etc which are hard to approximate in general graphs. Many of these remain NP-hard even in planar graphs. Later the technique was generalized to a broader class of graphs called graphs of bounded local treewidth [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . For a vertex v of a graph G and integer k ≥ 0, by G k v we denote the subgraph of G induced by vertices within distance at most k from v in G. A class of graphs G is of bounded local treewidth if there exists function f such that for every graph G ∈ G and every vertex v of G, treewidth(G k v ) ≤ f (k).",
